After reading: https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/manage-hugepages/scheduling-hugepages/ and https://clouddocs.f5.com/service-proxy/latest/spk-manual-cpu.html#hugepages I think this change may break Example CNF that requests hugepages-1Gi to the API (https://github.com/rh-nfv-int/testpmd-lb-operator/blob/4c96bfda3ccb34062b58e1cf9fd250f7d78023e8/roles/loadbalancer/templates/deployment.yml#L74). 

It looks like you can "allocate multiple huge page sizes", so the app will request: hugepages-2Mi or hugepages-1Gi depending on its configuration: https://docs.openshift.com/container-platform/4.7/scalability_and_performance/cnf-performance-addon-operator-for-low-latency-nodes.html

So, I think you should be able to define something like:
    pages:
      - size: "1G"
        count: 32
        node: 0
      - size: "1G"
        count: 32
        node: 1
      - size: "2M"
        count: 4000
        node: 0
      - size: "2M"
        count: 4000
        node: 1

Thanks!

> In addition, do you know if the servers have enough memory to handle 32 pages of 1G + 4000 pages of 2M?

Hello Charles. Yes, there should be enough room for the Hugepages. The servers have 503GB of RAM, so: 
 - Example-CNF is requesting 32GB
 - SPK is requesting 4000x2MB, 8GB

I was also reading this https://github.com/openshift-kni/performance-addon-operators/blob/master/docs/performance_profile.md, so you may want to disable the default size (defaultHugepagesSize: "1G"): 
HugePages defines a set of huge pages related parameters. It is possible to set huge pages with multiple size values at the same time. For example, hugepages can be set with 1G and 2M, both values will be set on the node by the performance-addon-operator. It is important to notice that setting hugepages default size to 1G will remove all 2M related folders from the node and it will be impossible to configure 2M hugepages under the node.

Cheers

Patch Set 28:

Ramon, thanks for providing the f5 references and for preparing this change.

I have a few questions/comments:

I read some comments in this PR from Tony (Aug 20) about using separate PAO profiles, and use variable "performance_definition" to define which profile to use, May I bring this question back? Just trying to understand if might be better to define a profile for each type of configuration we need (specially if f5 spk requires specific settings), or are we trying to produce a profile that could match all scenarios? 

About the CPU configuration, I share Jorge's opinion, so let's sort this out together: 

In Dallas servers we have 2 sockets => 20 cores per socket => each socket has 2 threads because of HT, so that give us 80 cores. 

Per the f5 doc there are some limitations[1]. Also reading about the manual-cpu guidelines[2] makes me think we should at least consider the following:

- Should we disable HT, (we don't need to disable in the BIOS, we can control during runtime[3], we can discuss this separately) 
- We should not use core IDs 0 and 1 per socket.
- Assuming we disable HT, then socket 1 should contain cores: 0-19, and socket 2: 20-39,

Finally, I was checking patchset 26/27 when you were testing two groups of hugepages configuration, and I noticed we are using (defaultHugepagesSize: "1G"): and Per Beto's comments in Aug 30: "It is possible but it is important to notice that setting hugepages default size to 1G will remove all 2M related folders from the node and it will be impossible to configure 2M hugepages under the node." So we might want to remove that default setting if we want to setup multiple hugepages configurations.

I think our current PAO basic profile somehow provides a viable configuration for most workloads, but if we want to be strict and follow the recommendation of f5 or other workload we need to shape it a little bit more. For example I was thinking if we prepare an f5 PAO profile we can be even more accurate and use the cores of the NUMA node where f5 interfaces will be connected only ( ens3f0 and ens3f1 in NUMA node 1), just some thoughts. 


[1]https://clouddocs.f5.com/service-proxy/latest/spk-openshift-requirements.html#scheduler-limitations
[2]https://clouddocs.f5.com/service-proxy/latest/spk-manual-cpu.html#allocation-guidelines
[3]https://access.redhat.com/solutions/rhel-smt

Thank you for all the details 😊
About the CPU configuration, you are assuming right about the Numa topology. I think the changes we made are finally not needed. We faced some issue at the beginning because the loadbalancer was expecting specific CPU to run and it was hardcoded in the config. It has been changed, we should try an install with the previous CPU layout.

About the performance profile, it is not possible to have a node in 2 different MCP and the POA is creating one per profile. If we create a profile dedicated to the loadblancer, we remove 2 nodes from the CNF_pool! That's why I was pushing to have one profile compatible with the lb and the CNF run but it may be not possible.

Patch Set 1:

The idea of the fix is to make dci-check-change using oc binary from kubeconfig folder.

before (hv5):
```
+ oc --kubeconfig /var/lib/dci-openshift-agent/clusterconfigs-ocp4/kubeconfig version
/usr/bin/dci-check-change: line 108: oc: command not found
+ echo 'Unable to use /var/lib/dci-openshift-agent/clusterconfigs-dciokd/kubeconfig to connect to OCP'
```

after (hv5):
```
+ OC_CLIENT=/var/lib/dci-openshift-agent/clusterconfigs-dciokd/oc
+ /var/lib/dci-openshift-agent/clusterconfigs-dciokd/oc --kubeconfig /var/lib/dci-openshift-agent/clusterconfigs-dciokd/kubeconfig version
Client Version: 4.8.17
Server Version: 4.8.17
Kubernetes Version: v1.21.1+6438632
```

Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

I think it's a good idea to use the oc client from the clusterconfigs-* dir. 
I'll give you a +2 once the job finishes.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

LGTM. To test it, you can create a local copy of this new dci-check-change script and execute it to test a simple change, to confirm it works. With this it would be enough, I guess

Patch Set 1:

> I don't think we should copy the source in the rpm. If you need
 > source, you can use "yumdownloader --source rh-python35-zuul". I'm
 > ok with the README in the devel

This command gets you the original, unpatched source + the patches, so you have to apply the patches manually in order, before you can get the actual source for the webui. I made this package so that we don't have to apply the patches by hand.

Well you shouldn't be using a copy of the source for development, it's better to use a git clone so that you can commit and submit review directly. If you really want to use a copy of the source, then we can provide a one-liner to unpack the src.rpm and apply the patch.

The issue is that we'll have two copies of the zuul source, one in the src.rpm, one in the -devel.rpm.

 > > > don't have to apply the patches by hand.
 > >
 > > Well you shouldn't be using a copy of the source for development,
 > > it's better to use a git clone so that you can commit and submit
 > > review directly. If you really want to use a copy of the source,
 > > then we can provide a one-liner to unpack the src.rpm and apply
 > the
 > > patch.
 > >
 > > The issue is that we'll have two copies of the zuul source, one
 > in
 > > the src.rpm, one in the -devel.rpm.
 > 
 > I find this pretty handy though for testing things out quickly.
 > I'll put this on WIP -1 and just add it to my future patches on
 > this distgit as needed during development.

I understand this is handy, but this is also unnecessary to bundle the source twice which result in a permanent cost for a few handy cases. Please document that snippet instead:

  yumdownloader --source rh-python35-zuul; rpm2cpio *.src.rpm | cpio -i; tar xzf *.tar.gz; pushd zuul*; for patch in $(awk '/Patch/ { print $2 }' ../zuul.spec); do patch -p1 < ../$patch; done

Thank you Bill.
This variable is very specific and only useful in some use cases, do you think it is absolutely necessary to document it ? 
I don't want to confuse user.

Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

Pierre, the change looks good to me, but I suggest to update the commit message, something like: this change allows to specify the number of nodes expected in the workers MCP with variable "mcp_worker_nodes". If we use customized_extramanifests_path to include a new MCP, that is secondary. wdyt?

IMHO, I do not think it's necessary to document it, the table in the README contains mustly dci_* vars, so if you want to document it maybe the inventory is a better place.

Patch Set 2:

> Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1
> 
> Pierre, the change looks good to me, but I suggest to update the commit message, something like: this change allows to specify the number of nodes expected in the workers MCP with variable "mcp_worker_nodes". If we use customized_extramanifests_path to include a new MCP, that is secondary. wdyt?

I see your point, I will adapt it :)
Yes, customized_extramanifests_path is secondary, but it is the only way to customize MCP, that why i would like to mention it.

> IMHO, I do not think it's necessary to document it, the table in the README contains mustly dci_* vars, so if you want to document it maybe the inventory is a better place.

The inventory is documented in the README, isn't it ?

Patch Set 3:

Thanks, it makes more sense for me now! 

> The inventory is documented in the README, isn't it ?
It is somehow documented, but as you might have seen, it's just an example of an inventory to use, and we keep that example with the minimum required variables to deploy, I was mostly thinking to add and document this variable in the respective inventory file you use for the deployment. However to keep it in the DCI repo, maybe add a small README or a vars/main.yml in the roles/prepare-cnf/ directory with a brief description of the variable? 

Personally I wouldn't worry to document this var, there is a bunch more not documented either, but if we want to start doing this as a good practice, maybe the role directory where the tasks using this variable are located could be a good start.

Beto, Ramon, Tony, and Jorge, thank you so much for the review! I decided to split the requested changes into several batches to test gradually. 

Step 1, current batch of changes.
In the current batch I do everything which does not require file split and refactoring: syntax / parsing / set_facts / tmp folder cleanup / documentation.
I'm also going to move preflight_operators_to_check from fake-cnf to example-cnf pipeline and test all this.

Step 2, refactoring and split into stages, next step.
There is a large task preflight_check_operator, and it would be nice to split it.

> Refactoring:
As suggested by Jorge and Beto, I'm going to move into separate task all mirroring and index image generation related to disconnected environment.

> Split by stages pre-run/run/post-run:
It's not really evident, because here I'm checking several operators in a loop: create resources / do tests (pods/jobs/operator install) / do cleanup and then again for the next operator.

Concerning pre-run, as suggested by Ramon and Beto, we could move mirroring of the "static" images and preflight runtime-assets into pre-run step.

Concerning post-run, we have to do cleanup of namespace and log folder after each operator and not just once during the teardown. 
First, to cleanup possible leftovers of non-successful operator installation during DeployableByOlm test. 
Second, because each test failure/success produces a unique set of log files (with not unique names!).

This line is maybe finally useful for people not using dci-openshift-agent-ctl but via the manual execution of the playbook like that:
cd /usr/share/dci-openshift-agent/
ansible-playbook dci-openshift-agent.yml -e @/etc/dci-openshift-agent/settings.yml

Patch Set 1:

Hello Sam, as we discussed on IM. Just adding a bit of feedback for your change.

I know it is still WIP but IMHO you may want to review the code created by Ramon/Fred to run the TNF test suite and do some refactor. I think you need to add code to mirror the image, and I do not think an ansible task for each supported test may be easy to maintain. The user should be able to provide a list of tests to execute against the chart, the values file etc. Then you get a report that will be uploaded to DCI.

Please take a look to:
https://github.com/redhat-cip/dci-openshift-app-agent/tree/master/roles

my understanding is that the role that you are working on should be able to test any helm chart if:
- Have the chart files
- Have the proper values for deployment
- Have a cluster with the proper resources
- Have a set of tests to run

In the case of nokia charts, those have multiple dependencies cluster network configurations and relationships with other charts. Maybe when you are done with your module and able to test generic charts we can think on testing one of the core Nokia-chf charts like the one that deploys Keycloak.  If we cannot deploy it on the cluster for a more extensive test maybe just run the general tests.

Hi Sam. Just to say that I fully agree with Beto's comments and advices. You will need to do something similar to what I did for the CNF Cert Suite (check the cnf-cert role in doaa) or what Tatiana is doing for preflight tests (check her CR: https://softwarefactory-project.io/r/c/dci-openshift-app-agent/+/22647).

Apart from this, I have seen you have included everything in an Ansible play. I would propose you to move the code to a role instead, as done for the CNF Cert Suite and preflight tests, and then to follow Beto's advices: include just one task to execute all the tests desired, defining the tests with a specific variable, and also including in a variable the container image you are using.

Hi Ramon, yes the plan is to enable and fix performance tests, we started with PR 22826 to address the namespace issue, my next move was going to include the performance test in the list of variable cnf_test_suites for all vanilla pipelines. 
I ran a test the other day to enable the performance tests in https://github.com/dci-labs/dallas-pipelines/pull/145 and I noticed that only 2 test failed because the POA namespace didn't match the rule, I think now that we fixed that we passed these fails but we got more now to fix, that were hidden before because of the NS validation. Interesting, i have some remarks:

  - It seems to me that it's not a search with partial name, for such a feature i would expect RHEL-8.Y to returns all RHEL-8 versions. In this patch, RHEL-8.Y returns the latest RHEL-8 version which is not straightforward to understand.
  - To get the latest it's relying on "models.TOPICS.c.created_at" which might be missleading, for example if topic RHEL-8.3 is deleted by error and recreated after, it will be considered the latest even if RHEL-8.4 is in place.
  - What would be the difference of doing a sort based on the topic name before returning the answer ?
